<br>
Uriel wrote:<br>
It was the first time in a few months I had been out of the tree city to visit the chaos below.  Young adventures were scurrying about everywhere, frantic, trying to stay away from oversized bees and ill tempered orcs.<br>
<br>
Using a minor spell I gave a young wood elf druid some agility and healed another gnome that had somehow wandered into Greater Faydark.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Cute little gnomes...gotta love em'&quot;, I thought to myself.<br>
<br>
It was at that moment a saw some familiar tracks in the leaf covered ground below my feet.  I leaned down and memories flooded back.  Though not a ranger of great season, I had become an adept tracker.  Yes, Hamadryad was on the move.<br>
<br>
I had heard rumors of the great guild leader stepping down from that most prestigious role.  She had to decided to go on a life adventure.<br>
<br>
&quot;I remember watching her drink several male barbarians under the table back when...&quot; I whispered in confidence to the listening trees.<br>
<br>
&quot;I remember her taking a stand for her beliefs in this guild and its beliefs.  Truly a remarkable woman&quot; , a smile formed on my face.<br>
<br>
As I sit here writing, I am reminiscing back to the days when the members in the guild could be counted on two hands and one foot.  <br>
<br>
&quot;How things change&quot;, the trees whispered back. <br>
<br>
I was startled.  Trees don't talk!<br>
<br>
&quot;Ohhh Uriel, ever the tracker and faithful guild member&quot;, Hamadryad stepped out from behind a large oak, <br>
<br>
Gaining my composure, I said &quot;tis good to see you m'lady&quot;, I did my kindest curtsey, but it felt awkward.<br>
<br>
Hama giggled and said, &quot;keep the acts of royalty for the high elves, Uriel&quot;  a sly mischievous smile appeared on her lips.<br>
<br>
We chatted of old times.  We chatted of good times, as well as the bad.  Though the bad times were few..they were tough.  We had made it through.  I could see the strength in her physical appearance, her eyes and her manner.<br>
<br>
I could see her fingers flexing and unflexing as if something awaited her.  I knew her visit would be short.<br>
<br>
I gave a broad, goofy smile and hugged the Adventurer, no longer a guild leader.<br>
<br>
&quot;So, what evil should be on the look out for you&quot; I asked in good humor.<br>
<br>
&quot;All of them&quot;, she laughed as she stepped into the shadows.<br>
<br>
I did not turn to see if I could spot her leave.  I did not worry about seeing her again.  <br>
<br>
I knew she would never leave us.<br>
